PiperOrigin-RevId: 366580744
Change-Id: Iff1f9a8c1ae7d565558fa12bbfe27fe642f6ad2f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/tensorflow/commits/38f4134e6884fb1d766999486a72810ebae6acf5"},{"sha":"9e3c906aca96739cc263fa1bc9671252fe084c9d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass to mark input-output pairs of cluster_func that read/write to same resource as aliases.

Earlier this was done for device variables only as part of tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass. Aliasing information (which enables HLO input/output buffer memory optimizations) need not be restricted to same constraints as tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass.

This change decouples this optimization from tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute and adds it as a new pass - tf-tpu-mark-input-output-aliases with relaxed constraints. This enables populating HloInputOutputAliasConfig in HloModuleProto even for those input-outputs corresponding to variables that cannot be merged with TPUExecute (for example, host resource variables) leading to input/output buffer optimization on device.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366623286
Change-Id: I502f381c58b7414bf402a9c5d2a3a4989cb36155","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/tensorflow/commits/9e3c906aca96739cc263fa1bc9671252fe084c9d"},{"sha":"13a747ba671c0e8e4d03c7fec33831fc72e44491","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Enable tf-device-mark-input-output-aliases pass in bridge phase 1 pipeline.

This captures input output pairs of device computation that read/write to the same resource variable. Passing that information to XLA compiler enables device memory optimization.

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

Some tests were using domain names that were intended to be "fake", but are
actually registered domain names (such as domain.com, registry.com, mytest.com).

Even though we were not actually making connections to these domains, it's
better to use domains that are designated for testing/examples in RFC2606:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2606

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

[{"sha":"b31c2073f058ee979e2085473ffff274f82eeefd","author":{"name":"Dimitris Vardoulakis","email":"532a0f5dcb324b87a62941a290161c72e1fa9537@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:HLO] Cleanly destruct fusion instructions and their computations.

If a fusion instruction dies before its computation, the computation becomes unreachable, but it may not be destructed until later. In this case, we need to clear its back-pointer to the fusion instruction, otherwise it will point to freed memory. Similarly, when a fusion computation dies, we must clear the fusion instructions's called_computations_.

We also add a boolean field in HloComputation to determine if it is a fusion computation, since with this CL we can have (unreachable) fusion computations whose fusion instruction is null.

Last, do a nullptr check during module cloning, to avoid runtime errors due to unreachable computations.

[{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363538405
Change-Id: I914714d034291661a9efa6b14d6f3941200e5a04","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zer0se7en/tensorflow/commits/27447895fcef704f8134a5c72735941d39e89ba6"},{"sha":"0bb0d612563802e9c4c36e1c310c92ba2224154f","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fix missing func def's when using custom kernel creators

Previously, when using custom kernel creators the function library runtime being
passed to the custom `CreateKernel` call was the wrong one (different from
other `CreateKernel` call) which led to missing func def's in following
scenario:
1) Custom kernel creator is used.
2) `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateKernel` is called directly from
   `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateItem`.
3) The `item` uses a function library runtime overlay which contains func def's
   that are missing from `this`.

Change-Id: Ie3c19a336a453f9bfde06f78c082364679d19c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zer0se7en/tensorflow/commits/0bb0d612563802e9c4c36e1c310c92ba2224154f"},{"sha":"e96ae7913a2534f836a92b4a1aebf403a31d6b8a","author":{"name":"Katherine Wu","email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com"},"message":"Export StructuredCoder as an internal API.

StructuredCoder is the only thing that decodes the input signatures from the SavedModel concrete functions, and Keras uses it to build the layers loaded from config. The layers must be built before loading the other functions/objects from the SavedModel in order to prevent them from creating new sublayers (which would not have the correct weights). Thus, we can't remove the use of StructuredCoder from Keras right now.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366580744
Change-Id: Iff1f9a8c1ae7d565558fa12bbfe27fe642f6ad2f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sujitahirrao/tensorflow/commits/38f4134e6884fb1d766999486a72810ebae6acf5"},{"sha":"9e3c906aca96739cc263fa1bc9671252fe084c9d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass to mark input-output pairs of cluster_func that read/write to same resource as aliases.

Earlier this was done for device variables only as part of tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass. Aliasing information (which enables HLO input/output buffer memory optimizations) need not be restricted to same constraints as tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass.

This change decouples this optimization from tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute and adds it as a new pass - tf-tpu-mark-input-output-aliases with relaxed constraints. This enables populating HloInputOutputAliasConfig in HloModuleProto even for those input-outputs corresponding to variables that cannot be merged with TPUExecute (for example, host resource variables) leading to input/output buffer optimization on device.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366623286
Change-Id: I502f381c58b7414bf402a9c5d2a3a4989cb36155","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sujitahirrao/tensorflow/commits/9e3c906aca96739cc263fa1bc9671252fe084c9d"},{"sha":"13a747ba671c0e8e4d03c7fec33831fc72e44491","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Enable tf-device-mark-input-output-aliases pass in bridge phase 1 pipeline.

This captures input output pairs of device computation that read/write to the same resource variable. Passing that information to XLA compiler enables device memory optimization.

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

Signed-off-by: Akihiro Suda <akihiro.suda.cz@hco.ntt.co.jp>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933"},{"sha":"97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use designated test domains (RFC2606) in tests

Some tests were using domain names that were intended to be "fake", but are
actually registered domain names (such as domain.com, registry.com, mytest.com).

Even though we were not actually making connections to these domains, it's
better to use domains that are designated for testing/examples in RFC2606:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2606

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

being unwrapped. This makes the QDQ inserting more flexible because all the

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sparrc/moby/commits/77096349e185923ff64f1c5dcf38a3c8d10a11b6"},{"sha":"42dba8c3f9a821c64864c49e60fff9b3ba3e86c5","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

however `unix.Stat_t.Mode` contains both file type and mode.

This patch strips file type so that only file mode is included in the Device.

Thanks to Iceber Gu, who noticed the same issue in containerd and runc.

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

Some tests were using domain names that were intended to be "fake", but are
actually registered domain names (such as domain.com, registry.com, mytest.com).

Even though we were not actually making connections to these domains, it's
better to use domains that are designated for testing/examples in RFC2606:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2606

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

This cl extracted the logic of the LowerCustomOps into an utility method so it
can be invoked the PrepareTf pass. Between the LowerCustomOps pass and the
PrepareTf pass, there is a shape inference pass and it will not work with the
tfl.TfCustomOp if it doesn't have a shape inference trait. This pass added a
simple shape inference for the wrapped tf.FakeQuant* ops.

[{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

Signed-off-by: Akihiro Suda <akihiro.suda.cz@hco.ntt.co.jp>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/moby/commits/62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933"},{"sha":"97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use designated test domains (RFC2606) in tests

Some tests were using domain names that were intended to be "fake", but are
actually registered domain names (such as domain.com, registry.com, mytest.com).

Even though we were not actually making connections to these domains, it's
better to use domains that are designated for testing/examples in RFC2606:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2606

[{"sha":"012cfa504954d97f318c160cd54b8c28b488d91a","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Improved filtering of IR dumps in MLIR bridge for debugging

- added filter for strings such that IR is only dumped if the serialized
  operation on which a pass is invoked contains any of the specified strings as
  a substring (filter is specified by environment variable
  `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_STRING_FILTER`)
- renamed `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_PATTERNS` to `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER`
- now `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER` uses exact match instead of substring match;
  previously, substring match was used because many pass names used to include
  full namespace qualification which is not the case anymore for most passes
  since the MLIR bridge Fixit
- now semicolon is used as separator instead of comma (so strings can contain commas that frequently occur in IR)

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366831215

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

Change-Id: If58332079e7ad64dbf32968ae27af4fb5ba2ed06","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/8d550d155dd659d4cd912ba883e67eee2e0203e3"},{"sha":"012cfa504954d97f318c160cd54b8c28b488d91a","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Improved filtering of IR dumps in MLIR bridge for debugging

- added filter for strings such that IR is only dumped if the serialized
  operation on which a pass is invoked contains any of the specified strings as
  a substring (filter is specified by environment variable
  `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_STRING_FILTER`)
- renamed `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_PATTERNS` to `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER`
- now `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER` uses exact match instead of substring match;
  previously, substring match was used because many pass names used to include
  full namespace qualification which is not the case anymore for most passes
  since the MLIR bridge Fixit
- now semicolon is used as separator instead of comma (so strings can contain commas that frequently occur in IR)

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

Signed-off-by: Akihiro Suda <akihiro.suda.cz@hco.ntt.co.jp>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933"},{"sha":"97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use designated test domains (RFC2606) in tests

Some tests were using domain names that were intended to be "fake", but are
actually registered domain names (such as domain.com, registry.com, mytest.com).

Even though we were not actually making connections to these domains, it's
better to use domains that are designated for testing/examples in RFC2606:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2606

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

[{"sha":"e72a03782cf5a884923e7ea59f6a54afc71929a3","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: add post-commit hook

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

This commitR addresses both issues:

1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

* Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/e72a03782cf5a884923e7ea59f6a54afc71929a3"}]

[{"sha":"97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use designated test domains (RFC2606) in tests

Some tests were using domain names that were intended to be "fake", but are
actually registered domain names (such as domain.com, registry.com, mytest.com).

Even though we were not actually making connections to these domains, it's
better to use domains that are designated for testing/examples in RFC2606:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2606

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

being unwrapped. This makes the QDQ inserting more flexible because all the

fake_quant_utils.

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

[{"sha":"62b5194f627571c019907edb11bb7bc2edd59933","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes (kernel >= 4.18)

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

  operation on which a pass is invoked contains any of the specified strings as
  a substring (filter is specified by environment variable
  `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_STRING_FILTER`)

- now `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER` uses exact match instead of substring match;
  previously, substring match was used because many pass names used to include
  full namespace qualification which is not the case anymore for most passes
  since the MLIR bridge Fixit
- now semicolon is used as separator instead of comma (so strings can contain commas that frequently occur in IR)

- added filter for strings such that IR is only dumped if the serialized
  operation on which a pass is invoked contains any of the specified strings as
  a substring (filter is specified by environment variable
  `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_STRING_FILTER`)
- renamed `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_PATTERNS` to `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER`
- now `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER` uses exact match instead of substring match;
  previously, substring match was used because many pass names used to include
  full namespace qualification which is not the case anymore for most passes
  since the MLIR bridge Fixit
- now semicolon is used as separator instead of comma (so strings can contain commas that frequently occur in IR)

[{"sha":"365a43dea79dd94726200d5ba25f7343d14f010f","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command+backend: generalized "plan mode"

So far we've only had "normal mode" and "destroy mode", where the latter
is activated either by "terraform plan -destroy" or "terraform destroy".

In preparation for introducing a third mode "refresh only" this
generalizes how we handle modes so we can potentially deal with an
arbitrary number of modes, although for now we only intend to have three.

Mostly this is just a different implementation of the same old behavior,
but there is one small user-visible difference here: the "terraform apply"
command now accepts a -destroy option, mirroring the option of the same
name on "terraform plan", which in turn makes "terraform destroy"
effectively a shorthand for "terraform apply -destroy".

This is intended to make us consistent that "terraform apply" without a
plan file argument accepts all of the same plan-customization options that
"terraform plan" does, which will in turn avoid us having to add a new
alias of "terraform plan" for each new plan mode we might add. The -help
output is changed in that vein here, although we'll wait for subsequent
commit to make a similar change to the website documentation just so we
can deal with the "refresh only mode" docs at the same time.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/365a43dea79dd94726200d5ba25f7343d14f010f"}]

[{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

can be invoked the PrepareTf pass. Between the LowerCustomOps pass and the

being unwrapped. This makes the QDQ inserting more flexible because all the
min/max operands of the tf.FakeQuant* ops have been folded already.

This patch also moves the related rewrites from the prepare_tf file to the
fake_quant_utils.

Change-Id: If58332079e7ad64dbf32968ae27af4fb5ba2ed06","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/8d550d155dd659d4cd912ba883e67eee2e0203e3"},{"sha":"012cfa504954d97f318c160cd54b8c28b488d91a","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Improved filtering of IR dumps in MLIR bridge for debugging

- added filter for strings such that IR is only dumped if the serialized
  operation on which a pass is invoked contains any of the specified strings as
  a substring (filter is specified by environment variable
  `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_STRING_FILTER`)
- renamed `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_PATTERNS` to `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER`
- now `MLIR_BRIDGE_LOG_PASS_FILTER` uses exact match instead of substring match;
  previously, substring match was used because many pass names used to include
  full namespace qualification which is not the case anymore for most passes
  since the MLIR bridge Fixit
- now semicolon is used as separator instead of comma (so strings can contain commas that frequently occur in IR)

[{"sha":"ba76fe9ff54cdc0be4b4a8f916c081fa5bfe9819","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Generalize the idea of a "plan mode", vs just destroy flag

Previously there were only two planning modes: normal mode and destroy
mode. In that context it made sense for these to be distinguished only by
a boolean flag.

We're now getting ready to add our third mode, "refresh only". This
establishes the idea that planning can be done in one of a number of
mutually-exclusive "modes", which are related to but separate from the
various other options that serve as modifiers for the plan operation.

This commit only introduces the new plans.Mode type and replaces the
existing "destroy" flag with a variable of that type. This doesn't cause
any change in effective behavior because Terraform Core still supports
only NormalMode and DestroyMode, with NewContext rejecting an attempt to
create a RefreshMode context for now.

It is in retrospect a little odd that the "destroy" flag was part of
ContextOpts rather than just an argument to the Plan method, but
refactoring that would be too invasive a change for right now so we'll
leave this as a field of the context for now and save revisiting that for
another day.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ba76fe9ff54cdc0be4b4a8f916c081fa5bfe9819"}]

[{"sha":"97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use designated test domains (RFC2606) in tests

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

[{"sha":"5f6b66250212b6c7d5668553e6d49388c7bb273f","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

Signed-off-by: Cam <gh@sparr.email>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sparrc/moby/commits/5f6b66250212b6c7d5668553e6d49388c7bb273f"}]

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

[{"sha":"97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use designated test domains (RFC2606) in tests

Some tests were using domain names that were intended to be "fake", but are
actually registered domain names (such as domain.com, registry.com, mytest.com).

Even though we were not actually making connections to these domains, it's
better to use domains that are designated for testing/examples in RFC2606:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2606

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bai/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

[{"sha":"97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use designated test domains (RFC2606) in tests

Some tests were using domain names that were intended to be "fake", but are
actually registered domain names (such as domain.com, registry.com, mytest.com).

Even though we were not actually making connections to these domains, it's
better to use domains that are designated for testing/examples in RFC2606:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2606

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/97a5b797b6f4c3f600d134e2fdd130bbaa2a617e"},{"sha":"00cb3073f4bfe7a24302aba8df87b37a33c99697","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix flaky TestInspect

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")
